## Selenium Interview Cheat Sheet (Python-ready)

1. What is Selenium?
- Open-source tool for automating web applications
- Used for UI automation testing
- Supports multiple browsers like Chrome, Firefox, and Edge
- Supports programming languages such as Python, Java, and C#
- Used for functional and regression testing
- Integrates with CI/CD pipelines for automated execution

2. What is Selenium mainly used for?
- Mainly used to automate web application testing
- Performs funcitonal testing -> Verifies features like login, search, forms
- Performs regression testing -> Ensures new changes don't break existing features
- Supports cross-browser testing (Chrome, FireFox, Edge)
- Automates repetative tasks to save time and effort
- Used for real scenarios like automated login and form submission using WebDriver

3. What are the important facts about Selenium?
- Selenium is open-source and free to use
- Supports major browsers like Chrome, FireFox, and Edge
- Works multiple languages : Python, Java, and C#
- Has key components : WebDriver, Grid, and IDE
- Supports cross-platform execution (Windows, macOS, Linux)
- Easily integrates with CI/CD pipelines

4. What are the main components of Selenium?
Selenium has THREE main components
- WebDriver -> Automates browsers and performs real user actions (click, type, navigate)
- IDE -> Browser plugin used for record & playback (good for beginners)
- Grid -> Enables parallel execution on multiple machines and browsers
- Grid support cross-browser and cross-platform testing
- WebDriver is the most commonly used component in real projects.

5. What is Selenium WebDriver?
- Selenium WebDriver is the core component of selenium used for browser automation
- Simulates real user actions like open website, click, type, submit, and navigate
- Directly communicates with the browser (no middle server like selenium RC)
- Faster and more reliable for modern web application
- Supports multiple browsers (Chrome, Edge, Firefox)
- Most widely used component in real-world automation projects(Python/Java etc)
<!-- Reliable means WebDriver provides consistent and stable test execution with fewer random failures -->

6. What is Selenium IDE?
- It is a browser extension used for recording and playback of test actions
- Automatically records user actions and generates test scripts
- Used for beginners and quick prototypes
- Uses "Selenese" commands and can export script to Python, Java and C#
- Works on Chrome, Firefox, and Edge (Chromium-based)
- Less flexible and poweful compared to WebDriver

7. What is Selenium Grid?
- It is used to run tests in parallel across multiple machines
- Supports cross-browser and cross-platform testing (different browsers & OS)
- Follow Hub-Node architecture
    - Hub -> controls test execution
    - Nodes -> Executes test on different environments
- Helps speed up execution of large test suites
- Improves test coverage and efficiency

8. What is Selenium RC?
- It is an older selenium tool used before WebDriver
- Required a server (middle layer) to communicate with the browser
- Slower and had a complex setup compared to WebDriver
- Less efficient for modern web applications
- Deprecated and no longer needed
- Replaced by Selenium WebDriver

9. How is WebDriver different from RC?
- WebDriver communicates directly with the browser, while RC required a server
- WebDriver is faster, simpler and more reliable
- WebDriver supports modern web applications (AJAX, dynamic content)
- RC is deprecated, while WebDriver is actively used
- WebDriver is better performance and stability

10. Can Selenium be used for mobile testing?
- It is mainly for web automation, not native mobile apps
- It can automate mobile browsers (like Chome on andriod, Safari on iOS)
- For full mobile testing (apps), use Appium
- Appium supports Andriod and iOS applications (native, hybrid, web)
- Appium uses the WebDriver API, so selenium knowledge can be reused

11. Whar are the advantages of Selenium?
- Open-source and free to use
- Supports multiple browsers (Chrome, Firefox and Edge) and multiple languages (Python, Java , C#)
- Works accross platforms: Windows, Linux, macOS
- Easily integrates with CI/CD pipelines (Jenkins, GitHub Actions)
