38. What is the best locator strategy in Selenium?
- Recommended priority for reliability & speed:
  1. ID → fastest, unique, use whenever available
  2. NAME → second choice, common in forms
  3. CSS SELECTOR → fast, flexible
  4. XPATH → very powerful, slightly slower
  5. CLASS NAME → less reliable if multiple classes exist
  6. TAG NAME → useful for groups of elements
  7. LINK TEXT → exact hyperlink text
- Always try to use the most unique and stable locator to avoid flaky tests

39. Why Waits Are Needed in Selenium?
- Modern web applications often load elements dynamically
- Without waits, selenium may try to interact with elements before they appear, causing errors like:
    "NoSuchElementException" -> element not found in DOM
    "ElementNotVisibleException" -> Element exists But not visbile
- Waits ensure selenium pause execution until elements are present, visible, or clickable, making tests stable and reliable

40. Types of Waits in Selenium
- Implicit Wait
    - Applies to the entire script
    - Selenium waits globally before locating elements
    -syntax
        driver.implicitly_wait(10)  # waits up to 10 seconds
    
- Explicit Wait
    - Applies to a specific element
    - Waits until a particular condition is met
    - syntax
        WebDriverWait(driver, 10).until(condition)
    
41. What is Explicit Wait?
- Tells Selenium to wait only until a specific condition occurs
- Examples:
    - Element appears
    - Element visible
    - Element clickable
    - Page title changes
- Advantage: Faster execution than time.sleep(), avoids unnecessary delays.

42. How Explicit Wait Works
- Uses:
    - WebDriverWait(driver, timeout)
    - Expected Conditions (EC)
- Example
    from selenium import WebDriver
    from selenium.webdriver.commom.by import By
    from selenium webdriver.support.ui import WebdriverWait
    from selenium.webdriver.support import expected_conditions as EC

    element = WebDriverWait(driver, 10).until(
        EC.present_of_element_located((By.ID, "username"))
        )
- Checks every 0.5 seconds (default polling time)
- Raises TimeoutException if condition not met

43. Common Expected Conditions
Condition & Purpose
-------------------
- title_is -> Waits until titile matches
- title_contains -> Waits until title contains text
- presence_of_element_located -> Wait until element exists in DOM
- visibility_of_element_located -> Wait until element is visible
- presence_of_all_elements_located -> Wait until multiple elements appear
- element_to_be_clickable -> Wait until element is clickable
- alert_is_present -> Wait until alert popup is appears
- Example
    EC.element_to_be_clickable((By.ID, "login"))

44. Explicit Wait vs time.sleep()
Feature & time.sleep() & explicit wait()
----------------------------------------
- waiting time -> fixed & up to maximum , stops when condition is met
- speed -> slower , faster
- best practice -> Not recommended , Recommended for dynamic elements
- Real-life analogy: Ordering food online
    - sleep(10) → waits full 10 sec even if ready in 3 sec
    - ExplicitWait → continues immediately when ready

45. Advantages of Explicit Wait
- Reliable handling of dynamic elements -> Waits only until a specific condition is met
- Improves test stability -> avoid flaky or inconsistent test failures
- Prevents unnecessary delays -> Continue immediately once condition is satisfied
- Reduce errors -> Fewer "NoSuchElememtException" or visibility issues  

46. What is Implicit Wait?
- Tells Selenium to wait for a maximum amount of time when searching for elements.
- If element is not immediately available:
    - Selenium keeps checking the DOM
    - Until element appears or timeout occurs
- Default: 0 seconds → Selenium checks immediately and raises exception if not found.
- Syntax
    driver.implicitly_wait(time_in_seconds)
- Example
    driver.implicitly_wait(10)

47. Characteristics of Implicit Wait
- Applied globally → affects all element searches in the script
- Set once → remains active for entire WebDriver session
- Simple to use, good for minor delays
- Example
    from selenium import webdriver

    driver = webdriver.Firefox()
    driver.implicitly_wait(10)  # applied to all find_element calls
    driver.get("https://www.example.com")

48. How Implicit Wait Works Internally
- Selenium checks repeatedly until timeout:
    0 sec → check element
    1 sec → check
    2 sec → check
    ...
    10 sec → timeout if not found
- If element appears earlier → Selenium continues immediately.

49. What are the advantages of using Implicit Wait in Selenium?
- Simple to implement -> Easy to add in your script
- Global effect -> Applies to all element searches in the webDriver session
- Reduces "NoSuchElementException" -> helps when elements take a short time to appear
- Handles minor dynamic loading -> Useful for small delays in page elements

50. What are the limitations of using Implicit Wait in Selenium?
- Aplies to all elements -> might wait unnecessarily for elements that are already present
- Less control -> cannot wait for specific conditions like visible, clickable
- Not suitable for complex dynamic elements -> Slow or unreliable for AJAX - heavy pages
- Cannot handle specific scenarios -> Only waits for element presence, not for other conditions

51. What are Action Chains in Selenium?
- Used to perform advanced user interactions on web elements
- Simulates real user behavior that ".click()" or ".send_keys()" cannot handle
- We use "ActionChains" class from selenium.webdriver.common action_chains
- Common actions:
    - Mouse hover
    - Right click
    - double click
    - Drag and Drop
    - Click and hold
    - Keyboard actions (CTRL, SHIFT, typing sequences)
- Example
    from selenium.webdriver.common.action_chains import ActionChains
    action = ActionChains(driver)
    action.move_to_element(element).perform()

52. Why Use Action Chains in selenium?
- Normal commands are limited: ".click()" and ".send_keys()" work only for simple interactions
- Handles complex actions: Needed for interactions like hover -> submenu click, drag & drop, or keyboard shortcuts
- Simulates real user behavior accurately for dynamic or interactive web elements
- Example:
    Hover over a "products" menu and click the "Laptop" submenu

53. How Action Chains Work in selenium?
- Create an ActionChains object:
    actions = ActionChains(driver)
- Queue the actions: Use methods like ".click()", ".move_to_element()", "drag & drop()", etc
- Execute the actions: Call ".perform()" to run all queued actions
- Actions are not performed immediately - They run only after ".perform" is called

54. Common ActionChains Methods
Action & Method
---------------
- click() -> Click element
- double_click() -> Double-click element
- context_click() -> Right click element
- click_and_hold() -> Hold mouse button
- release() -> Release mouse button
- move_to_element() -> Hover over element
- move_by_offset(x, y) -> move mouse by coordinates
- drag_and_drop(source, target) -> drag element to target
- key_down(key) -> Press key without releasing
- key_up(key) -> Release key
- send_keys(keys) -> send keyboard input
- pause(seconds) -> Pause action chain
- perform() -> Execute all queued actions

55. Example – Click an Element
    from selenium import webdriver
    from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
    from selenium.webdriver.common.action_chains import ActionChains

    driver = webdriver.Firefox()
    driver.get("https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/")
    element = driver.find_element(By.LINK_TEXT, "Courses")

    actions = ActionChains(driver)
    actions.click(element).perform()

56. Example – Mouse Hover
    menu = driver.find_element(By.ID, "menu")
    actions = ActionChains(driver)
    actions.move_to_element(menu).perform()
- Move mouse to element -> reveals hidden submenu

57. Example – Drag and Drop
    source = driver.find_element(By.ID, "drag")
    target = driver.find_element(By.ID, "drop")

    actions = ActionChains(driver)
    actions.drag_and_drop(source, target).perform()
- Clicks, holds, moves, and releases element to target.

58. Two Ways to Use ActionChains
- Chain pattern(single line):
    - Combines multiple actions in one line
    - Executes immediately using ".perform()"
    - Example
        ActionChains(driver).move_to_element(menu).click(submenu).perform()
- Queue pattern(Multiple lines):
    - Queue actions step by step
    - Execute all actions together at the end with ".perform()"
    - Example
        actions = ActionChains(driver)
        actions.move_to_element(menu)
        actions.click(submenu)
        actions.perform()
    
59. What is an Alert in Selenium?
- A browser popoup message box is used to:
    - Show information
    - Ask for confirmation
    - Ask for user input
- Examples
    - Login warning message
    - Delete confirmation dialogs
    - General alerts/warnings
- Alerts are outside DOM, so normal locators like "find_element" cannot interact with them.
- Must be selenium's Alert API (driver.switch_to.alert) to handle them

60. How to Handle Alerts in Selenium?
- Class used:
    from selenium.webdriver.common.alert import Alert
- Steps to handle alerts:
    - Accept an alert: alert.accept() -> Clicks "OK"
    - Dismiss an alert: alert.dismiss() -> Click "Cancel"
    - Get alert text: alert.text -> Retrieves message from alert
    - Send input to alert: alert.send_keys("text") -> For prompt alerts
- Example
    alert = driver.switch_to.alert
    print(alert.text) # Get alert message
    alert.accept() # Click ok

61. Common Alert Methods
Method & Description
--------------------
- accept() -> Click OK button
- dismiss() -> Click Cancle button
- send_keys("input") -> send input to alert
- text -> Get alert message text

62. Steps to Handle an Alert
- Open browser
- Navigate to webpage
- Trigger the alert
- Switch to alert -> alert=Alert(driver)
- Perform action-> accept(), dismiss(), send_keys() or text()

63. Example – Accept Alert
    from selenium import webdriver
    from selenium.webdriver.common.alert import Alert
    import time

    driver = webdriver.Firefox()
    driver.get("https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/")
    time.sleep(5)  # wait for alert to appear
    alert = Alert(driver)
    print(alert.text)
    alert.accept()  # clicks OK
    driver.quit()

64. Example – Dismiss Alert
    alert = Alert(driver)
    alert.dismiss()  # clicks Cancel

65. Example – Send Input to Alert
    alert = Alert(driver)
    alert.send_keys("Hello, Geeks!")
    alert.accept()  # submit input

66. Types of Alerts
- Simple Alert -> Message + OK button
    - use accept()
    - Example
        "Are you sure?"
- Confirmation Alert -> Message + OK/ Cancel buttons
    - use accept() -> OK
    - use dismiss() -> Cancel
    - Example
        "Do you want to delete this item?"
- Prompt Alert -> Messae + Input field + Ok/Cancel
    - Use send_keys("text") → enter input
