70. What are Exceptions in Selenium?
- Exceptions are errors that occur during program execution in selenium
- Common scenarios:
    - Element not found on the page
    - Element is hidden, disabled, or not interactable
    - Click or action cannot be performed on an element
    - Page takes too long to load
    - Alert or frame does not exist when switching
- Stops program execution unless the exception is handled using tr-except or explict waits
- Example:
    from selenium.webdriver.common.exceptions import NoSuchElementException
    try:
        element = driver.find_element("id", "my_element")
    except NoSuchElementException:
- Handling exceptions is critical for robust selenium scripts


71. Why Exceptions Occur in selenium?
- Wrong locators or typos in element identifiers
- Element not loaded yet due to dynamic element
- Element hidden, disabled or off-screen, so it cannot be interacted with
- Popup or overlay blocking interaction with the element
- Page taking too long to load, causing timeout or unavailability
- Exceptions often happen when selenium tries to interact with an element that is not ready or accessible, so using waits and correct locators helps prevent the

72. Common Selenium Exceptions
Exception & Description & Example Scenario
------------------------------------------
- NoSuchElementException - Element not found in DOM - Wrong locator or element not present
- ElementClickInterceptedException - Click blocked by another element - Popup, banner, overlay covering element
- ElementNotInteractableException - Element exists but cannot be interacted - Hidden input, disabled button
- ElementNotSelectableException - Trying to select a disabled dropdown option - <option value="banana" disabled>
- NoAlertPresentException - Alert is not present when expected - Calling Alert(driver) when no alert
- NoSuchFrameException - Frame not found - Switching to a non-existent iframe
- NoSuchWindowException - Window not found - Switching to a closed window
- TimeoutException - Page or element took too long to load - Waiting beyond explicit wait time
- StaleElementReferenceException - Element no longer attached to DOM - Page refresh removed element reference
- InvalidSelectorException - Locator syntax is wrong - Malformed XPath or CSS selector

73. Example – Handling Exceptions
    from selenium import webdriver
    from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
    from selenium.common.exceptions import NoSuchElementException

    driver = webdriver.Chrome()
    driver.get("https://www.geeksforgeeks.org")

    try:
        element = driver.find_element(By.ID, "login")
        element.click()
    except NoSuchElementException:
        print("Element not found")
    finally:
        driver.quit()

74. Why Exception Handling is Important?
- Prevents test failures
- Makes automation scripts stable
- Handles dynamic web elements
- Improves reliability and robustness of tests

